  "vulnerability_information": "When curl  send a request with `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` using HTTP/1.1, and follows a redirect to an HTTP/2 endpoint, the `upload_chunky` flag is not properly reset. As a result, the `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` header is sent in the subsequent request even when HTTP/2 is negotiated/used.\n\nThis violates RFC 9113 (HTTP/2) which states that HTTP/2 uses its own farming and `Transfer-Encoding` header must not be used.\n\n##Proof OF Concept\nSetup:\nLocal test server with HTTP/1.1 ---> HTTPS (HTTP/2) redirect \n`Reproduction Command:`\n```bash\ncurl -vvv --http1.1 --no-alpn -L --http2 -k \\\n  -H \"Transfer-Encoding: chunked\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: text/plain\" \\\n  -d \"This is chunked encoding bug test data\" \\\n  http://test.local:8080/\n```\n##Observed Behavior:\n- First request (HTTP/1.1): `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` --> Correct\n- Second request (after redirect): 'Transfer-Encoding: chunked' is still present ---> Vulnerable Even with `--http2` flag, the header is not suppressed.\n\n##Root Cause\nin 'lib/http.c'\n- `http_req_set_TE()` and 'http_add_content_hds()' functions only check HTTP version at intial request setup.\n- During redirect handling ('Curl_follow_Location()' / new Request setup), the 'data->req.upload_chunky' falg is not relible reset when protocol changes from HTTP/1.1 ---> HTTP/2.\n\n## Impact\n\n- Protocol confusion between client and server / proxies.\n- potential for `HTTP Request Smuggling / Desync attack` in enviroments with reverse proxies or CDNs that handle HTTP/1.1 <--> HTTP/2 translation.\n- Unexpected behavior in middleboxes and caching systems.",
  "weakness": {
